Discovering the Remote üåç

Few places on Earth offer the chance to photograph wild bonobos, our closest living relatives. These incredible creatures exclusively inhabit the dense tropical forests of Central Africa, both to the north and south of the Congo River.

For nearly three decades, German researchers Barbara Fruth and Gottfried Hohmann, affiliated with the Max-Planck-Institute for Animal Behavior, have dedicated themselves to the study of wild bonobos. A significant portion of this research has taken place over 18 years at Lui Kotale.

This aerial view captures the vast, unspoiled primary forest surrounding the Lui Kotale research camp, nestled on the fringes of Salonga National Park in the DRC.

Follow along as we share the story of this remote wilderness and the remarkable bonobos that call it home.

